Interview Questions
1. What is encapsulation in Java?
-->Encapsulation is the process of wrapping data (variables) and methods (behavior) together into a single unit called a class,
    and restricting direct access to the data using access modifiers.
    It is mainly achieved by:
    Declaring variables as private
    Providing public getter and setter methods
    
    Example:
    class Student {
        private String name;
    
        public void setName(String name) {
            this.name = name;
        }
    
        public String getName() {
            return name;
        }
    }



2. How is encapsulation different from abstraction?
-->
| Encapsulation                                        | Abstraction                                    |
| ---------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------- |
| Hides internal data                                  | Hides implementation details                   |
| Focuses on data security                             | Focuses on simplicity                          |
| Achieved using private variables and getters/setters | Achieved using abstract classes and interfaces |
| “How data is protected”                              | “What to show to user”                         |

Example:
Encapsulation → ATM protects account balance internally.
Abstraction → User only sees withdraw/deposit options.



3. Why is encapsulation important in object-oriented programming?
-->Encapsulation is important because it:
    Protects data from unauthorized access
    Improves security
    Increases maintainability
    Makes code reusable
    Allows controlled access to variables
    Reduces dependency between classes



4. How do you achieve encapsulation in Java?
-->Encapsulation is achieved by:

    Declaring class variables as private
    Providing public getter and setter methods
    
    Example:
    
    class Employee {
        private int salary;
    
        public int getSalary() {
            return salary;
        }
    
        public void setSalary(int salary) {
            if(salary > 0) {
                this.salary = salary;
            }
        }
    }



5. What are the benefits of using private variables in a class?
-->Benefits:
    Prevents direct modification
    Provides data security
    Allows validation before updating values
    Makes class behavior controlled
    Improves maintainability


6. Can you give a real time example of encapsulation in Java?
-->A bank account is a real-time example.
    
    Balance is hidden (private)
    Users access it through methods like:
    deposit()
    withdraw()
    getBalance()
    
    Example:
    
    class BankAccount {
        private double balance;
    
        public void deposit(double amount) {
            balance += amount;
        }
    
        public double getBalance() {
            return balance;
        }
    }




7. What is the role of getters and setters in encapsulation?
-->Getter → Used to read/access data
    Setter → Used to modify/update data
    
    They provide controlled access to private variables.
    
    Example:
    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }
    
    public void setName(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }



8. Is encapsulation possible without access modifiers?
-->No.
    Access modifiers are important for proper encapsulation.
    
    Without private, variables can be accessed directly from outside the class, which breaks data hiding.



9. What happens if you make all fields public? Is it still encapsulation?
-->No.
    If all variables are public:
        Any class can directly modify data
        No control or validation exists
        Data security is lost
        
    Example:
        class Student {
            public int marks;
        }
        
        This is not proper encapsulation.



10. How does encapsulation improve code maintainability?
-->Encapsulation improves maintainability because:
    
    Internal implementation can change without affecting external code
    Bugs become easier to manage
    Code becomes modular and organized
    
    Example:
        You can change internal logic inside setter methods without changing external code.



11. Can you explain how encapsulation helps in securing data?
-->Encapsulation protects data by:
        
        Restricting direct access using private
        Allowing controlled access through methods
        Performing validation before updating data
        
        Example:
        
        public void setAge(int age) {
            if(age > 0) {
                this.age = age;
            }
        }
        Invalid values are prevented.



12. Why should we avoid exposing too many getters and setters?
-->Exposing too many getters and setters is often considered a "code smell" because it fundamentally undermines the core principle 
    of encapsulation. While they provide a controlled way to access private fields, overusing them effectively makes your private data
    public, just with a different syntax.

        Too many getters/setters:
            Reduce security
            Expose internal structure
            Increase tight coupling
            Allow unnecessary modification
            
        Good encapsulation exposes only required methods.



13. How does encapsulation relate to the concept of immutability?
-->Immutable classes are strongly encapsulated.
        
        In immutable classes:
            Variables are private
            No setters are provided
            Values cannot change after object creation
            
            Example:
            
            final class Person {
                private final String name;
            
                public Person(String name) {
                    this.name = name;
                }
            
                public String getName() {
                    return name;
                }
            }



14. Can you encapsulate a class that has static fields?
-->Yes.
    Static fields can also be private and accessed through static getter/setter methods.
    Example:
    class Company {
        private static String companyName;
    
        public static String getCompanyName() {
            return companyName;
        }
    }



15. What is the difference between encapsulation and information hiding?
-->
| Encapsulation                     | Information Hiding                     |
| --------------------------------- | -------------------------------------- |
| Binding data and methods together | Restricting access to internal details |
| OOP concept                       | Security concept                       |
| Achieved using classes            | Achieved using access modifiers        |
Encapsulation supports information hiding.



16. Can you achieve encapsulation without using setter methods?
-->Yes.
    You can provide:
        Only getter methods (read-only)
        Constructor initialization
        
        Example:
        
        class Student {
            private final int id;
        
            public Student(int id) {
                this.id = id;
            }
        
            public int getId() {
                return id;
            }
        }


17. How does encapsulation interact with inheritance and polymorphism?
-->Encapsulation protects parent class data
    Child classes access data through protected/public methods
    Polymorphism works with encapsulated methods safely
    
    Example:
    
    class Animal {
        private String name;
    
        public String getName() {
            return name;
        }
    }
    Child classes cannot directly access name.
    

18. Can encapsulation be broken using reflection? How would you prevent it?
-->Yes.
    Reflection can access private fields using:
        field.setAccessible(true);

    Prevention:
        Use SecurityManager (older Java)
        Use modules (Java 9+)
        Avoid unnecessary reflection
        Use immutable classes where possible



