20. What are some anti-patterns that violate encapsulation?
-->Anti-patterns:
    
    Public variables
    Excessive getters/setters
    Returning mutable internal objects directly
    Exposing internal implementation details    
    Bad Example:
        public List<String> items;
    
    Better:
        private List<String> items;


21. Demonstrate encapsulation using interfaces and abstract classes.
-->Encapsulation means hiding internal implementation details and allowing access only through controlled methods.
In Java, we can demonstrate encapsulation using:

Interfaces → define what operations can be performed.
Abstract classes → provide partial implementation and protect data using private fields.
Example: Bank Account System
// Interface
interface AccountOperations {
    void deposit(double amount);
    void withdraw(double amount);
    void displayBalance();
}

// Abstract Class
abstract class BankAccount implements AccountOperations {

    // Encapsulated data (hidden)
    private double balance;

    // Constructor
    public BankAccount(double balance) {
        this.balance = balance;
    }

    // Protected method to access balance safely
    protected double getBalance() {
        return balance;
    }

    // Protected method to update balance safely
    protected void setBalance(double balance) {
        this.balance = balance;
    }

    // Common implementation
    public void deposit(double amount) {
        if (amount > 0) {
            balance += amount;
            System.out.println("Deposited: " + amount);
        }
    }

    // Abstract method
    public abstract void withdraw(double amount);
}

// Concrete Class
class SavingsAccount extends BankAccount {

    public SavingsAccount(double balance) {
        super(balance);
    }

    @Override
    public void withdraw(double amount) {
        if (amount <= getBalance()) {
            setBalance(getBalance() - amount);
            System.out.println("Withdrawn: " + amount);
        } else {
            System.out.println("Insufficient Balance");
        }
    }

    @Override
    public void displayBalance() {
        System.out.println("Current Balance: " + getBalance());
    }
}

// Main Class
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        SavingsAccount acc = new SavingsAccount(5000);

        acc.deposit(2000);
        acc.withdraw(1500);
        acc.displayBalance();
    }
}

